<TEXT>
britain france and australia announced thursday 
they are sending ships and planes to the persian gulf in response 
to us appeals for help with a multinational force to defend saudi 
arabia against iraq 
us officials were busy thursday trying to muster global 
support for the force sent in to defend against any iraqi invasion 
of saudi arabia which neighbors iraq and kuwait however only 
britain and australia announced they would send hardware and troops 
as part of the force 
french president francois mitterrand announced thursday evening 
that his nation was increasing its naval and air forces in the gulf 
as needed to intervene if necessary 
he said they would coordinate with the international force but 
remain under french command 
british officials said they would immediately send two fighter 
aircraft squadrons antiaircraft missiles and other air and sea 
forces totaling more than 1000 men to the persian gulf 
defense secretary tom king told a news conference that britain 
will send a squadron of tornado f3 fighter jets from cyprus and a 
squadron of jaguar groundattack fighters from england as well as 
a number of nimrod maritime patrol aircraft the ministry of 
defense said each squadron includes 12 planes 
two british frigates will arrive in the gulf this weekend to 
join the destroyer hms york and three minesweepers will be 
deployed initially to the eastern mediterranean king said a 
squadron of rapier groundtoair missiles is also being sent he 
said 
mitterrand said his country will send an aircraft carrier to the 
gulf region bolstering french naval and air forces already there 
to counter any new aggression by iraq 
after a twohour emergency cabinet meeting mitterrand also 
promised france will send war materials and technicians to the gulf 
as requested by saudi arabia and other states 
france will there as elsewhere continue to exist in 
solidarity and coordination with countries like the united states 
but only under french officers mitterrand told reporters 
in canberra australian prime minister bob hawke said his 
country will send two frigates and a supply ship as part of the 
international force 
he said they will be used to enforce the blockade on iraq and 
kuwait and protect the exports from other oilproducing 
countries he said 
western leaders have talked of a blockade if a unorganized 
global embargo against iraq fails 
i believe the gravity of the situation warranted this 
action hawke told a news conference 
he said the ships will be able to leave australia within five 
days and arrive within 22 days 
president saddam hussein of iraq whose forces invaded kuwait on 
aug 2 has denied any intention of attacking saudi arabia 
however western reports say his troops have massed on the saudi 
border 
us soldiers were steaming into saudi arabia on thursday 
the pentagon declined to detail the size of the us deployment 
but pentagon spokesman pete williams said all f15 fighters sent to 
saudi arabia had arrived as have five awacs reconnaissance planes 
six us warships stand by in the mediterranean and two aircraft 
carrier groups are positioned in the red and arabian seas he said 
mideastern diplomatic sources said the us buildup would total 
at least 40000 troops backed by more than 100 jet fighters 
italian premier giulio andreotti on thursday told british prime 
minister margaret thatcher that italy has not been asked to join 
the multinational force in saudi arabia according to the italian 
news agencies ansa and agi they cited unidentified sources in the 
premiers office 
his spokesman could not be reached to comment 
several nations including canada and the netherlands have said 
they will decide whether to participate in the usled force 
following separate meetings of the north atlantic treaty 
organization and european community foreign ministers in brussels 
belgium on friday 
portugal west germany italy and spain have offered use of 
bases greece on wednesday allowed nine us support planes to pass 
through its airspace on their way to the gulf 
egypt and morocco mentioned by us defense department sources 
as the likeliest arab participants refused to join president 
hosni mubarak of egypt proposed that an arab force act as a buffer 
between kuwait and iraq 
that proposal was expected to be on the agenda at an arab summit 
meeting in cairo which was postponed to friday 
us secretary of state james a baker iii who arrived in 
ankara on thursday indicated he may ask turkish president turgut 
ozal to permit the united states to use that countrys military 
bases as staging areas in the event of strikes against iraq 
it goes without saying that turkey is strategically very 
important baker said on his flight from washington turkey 
borders iraq 
