<TEXT>
a young soldier offered to plead 
guilty to a burglary he said he didnt commit so he could ship out 
for saudi arabia with his unit but a jury quickly found him 
innocent thursday and he was on his way 
pfc joseph cufferi 20 was accused of breaking into a 
neighbors house in october 1989 while home on leave 
cufferi said he got together with friends drank approximately 
10 beers and had some trouble getting into what he thought was 
his parents home 
he was actually two doors down at the home of robert anthony 
keller 
i remember ringing the doorbell and going around and saying 
let me in i thought that was my house cufferi said 
but when keller heard the backyard gate open and saw the 
darkclothed man trying the french doors he thought cufferi 
intended to hurt his family assistant state attorney thomas lawson 
told the palm beach county circuit court jury on wednesday 
he spent about 15 minutes knocking said assistant public 
defender karen ehrlich burglars dont knock 
keller said he told cufferi to leave but the soldier kept 
banging doors and windows so keller grabbed a shotgun pointed it 
through the window at cufferi and threatened to shoot keller said 
cufferi ran but was later caught by police and charged with 
attempted burglary 
im sorry i went to the wrong house but it was a mistake 
cufferi said wednesday but now i need to go do my job i defend 
the united states of america 
some members of his unit the 24th infantry based at fort 
stewart ga were due to leave thursday 
prosecutors agreed earlier in the week to allow cufferi to plead 
guilty to the lesser charge of trespassing but he rejected the 
deal however he changed his mind after learning his unit was 
shipping out apparently believing hed be allowed to go after 
pleading guilty 
but the kellers refused to go along with the deal and cufferi 
went on trial 
on thursday a hopeful cufferi parked his packed car near the 
courthouse 
the jury took only 15 minutes to decide his fate 
the first thing we did was take a vote and it was unanimous 
not guilty said juror tim kelly 
thursday night cufferis father said his son called from fort 
stewart to say hed arrived in time to catch up with his buddies 
im glad that at least through all of this he was able to be 
where he wants to be said jospeh cufferi sr 
</TEXT>
