<TEXT>
soldiers packed and shipped out to the middle east on wednesday 
leaving behind frightened civilians and tearful wives and fiancees 
others rode the rumor mill wondering if they would be the next to 
be mobilized 
theyre going they are definitely going there is no doubt in 
my mind that this is another war said effie parsons 23 a clerk 
at a convenience store near fort bragg nc home of the 82nd 
airborne division 
president bush ordered us forces to saudi arabia to help it 
repel a potential attack by iraq which invaded neighboring kuwait 
last week 
bush specifically mentioned the 82nd pentagon sources speaking 
on condition of anonymity said they also expected deployment of 
the 24th division mechanized from fort stewart ga and the 101st 
airborne division from fort campbell ky elements of those three 
units would be deployed with the 18th airborne corps a control 
unit at fort bragg that directs the combat divisions the sources 
said 
a soldier at fort bragg who spoke on condition of anonymity 
said about 2000 soldiers from there were to go to saudi arabia and 
that some of that force had left tuesday night 
on wednesday truckloads of soldiers and supplies were seen 
driving toward pope air force base which adjoins fort bragg at 
least two large civilian jetliners that could be used to haul 
soldiers landed at pope 
around 850 pm a steady stream of c141s began leaving the 
air base and continued leaving for at least 30 minutes at 
intervals of a few minutes about two hours later at least four 
planes were heard leaving or landing 
early in the week convenience store clerks said sales of 
chewing tobacco batteries and insect repellent were brisk as 
soldiers hurriedly stocked up 
a lot of fathers are coming in with their kids holding them 
real tight and many wives are in tears as they make their 
purchases said ms parsons 
assistant store manager wade felman comparing this deployment 
with the panamanian deployment of december 1989 said the 
atmosphere now is much more tense and wives coming in are more 
nervous 
the panamanian thing i guess seemed so small to them he 
said i think this thing is a little more worrisome 
one of the 82nds soldiers pfc mark ohmer was to marry angela 
nelson 19 in suburban detroit this saturday the 6000 wedding 
was postponed when he was called back to base 
it happened so fast im so upset nelson said iraq does 
a lot of chemical warfare and marks job is to deactivate chemical 
weapons and deactivate contamination of soldiers he also was 
taught to dismantle bombs 
while the pentagon sources said the 101st airborne also was 
going spokesmen for the 14000soldier division at fort cambpell 
continued to deny that wednesday 
that didnt convince people just outside the post gates in 
clarksville tenn and fort campbell ky 
everybodys a little nervous you never know what can 
happen said tammy bradford whose husband mike is a 101st 
infantryman mrs bradford at work at a restaurant said she tried 
not to think about the possibility that he could be ordered to the 
middle east 
i think we should be out there to stop iraq she said but 
i dont want my husband to go 
i feel somethings going on on the base at fort campbell that 
were not aware of and we shouldnt be aware of said morrell 
boyd owner of a cleaning shop in clarksville 
boyd said the number of soldiers bringing in uniforms to be 
cleaned or mended had not increased over the past two days but 
those that are coming in are needing it in a rush he said 
at fort stewart army officials tightened security wednesday 
night as members of the 24th infantry loaded their gear into 
deserttan trucks and bradley fighting vehicles 
army officials refused to say whether the division would deploy 
to saudi arabia to help protect the oil kingdom from an iraqi 
invasion but relatives braced for their departure and expressed 
concern for their safety 
maj ron keeling a fort stewart spokesman said the division 
was conducting a routine emergency deployment exercise 
some soldiers had been called back from leave 
helmeted soldiers armed with m16 rifles could be seen trudging 
through motor pools with rucksacks and duffel bags wives and 
girlfriends huddled with soldiers in parking lots a telephone 
operator said longdistance circuits were jammed with calls from 
fort stewart soldiers 
military police set up checkpoints at some entrances to the post 
spec 4 norman aimes 24 part of the infantry division said 
earlier that he was called back from leave in utah they called 
and said there is a 99 percent chance that we are going aimes 
said tuesday 
im worried said surshander armstrong wife of an army 
specialist at stewart if you knew exactly what they were going 
to do then the waiting wouldnt be so bad then you could prepare 
yourself 
