<TEXT>
a federal administrator appointed two years ago 
to help drive organized crime out of the fulton fish market said in 
a court report filed wednesday that racketeering remains rampant at 
the huge market 
in the report filed in us district court frank h wohl said 
the market was controlled by a few people who set rules for 
delivering seafood and practiced extortion 
he told the new york times in an interview published in thursday 
editions that strongarm tactics by some companies discouraged 
suppliers from sending fish to new york driving up retail prices 
for local consumers 
he told the times that city officials worsened the problem by 
abdicating their responsibility to regulate and police the market 
he said he would soon impose rules to help suppliers and businesses 
operate at the market without intimidation 
about 90 million pounds of seafood with a retail value of 2 
billion are sold each year at the market in lower manhattan 
wohl said in the report that city officials told him they feared 
for the safety of city employees involved in the market and also 
feared attempts to corrupt police officers if the city enforced 
regulations more strictly 
he said that although the city had the authority to license and 
regulate deliveries arriving truckers are assigned by some 
unknown authority to unload their trucks under this system his 
report said it costs as much to transport a pound of fish 50 feet 
at the market as it does to transport it from new england to new 
york city 
the unloaders charge the wholesalers 135 per 100pound box if 
truckers unloaded supplies themselves wohl said they would be 
subject to physical abuse 
drivers must pay extra to have their fish unloaded promptly he 
said 
jeanne nathan a spokeswoman for the city office of business 
development told the times wohls report was old news and 
reflected his inability to correct the problem despite a budget 
of 750000 and a staff of a dozen investigators and researchers 
</TEXT>
