<DOCNO> AP900809-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
hes been fixing typewriters for 
students secretaries and the literati for more than half a century 
in his dusty shop near yale university but time and technology 
have overrun manson h whitlock 
the typewriter is going the same way as the horse and buggy i 
guess it just isnt meant to be any more said whitlock 73 who 
will close his doors at the end of the month 
whitlock has worked on the typewriters of some of the countrys 
best known writers pulitzer prizewinners robert penn warren 
archibald macleish and john hersey biographer and historian 
william manchester and love story author erich segal 
before word processors and personal computers whitlock was part 
of a spring ritual at yale at the end of each school year 
hundreds of students would drop off their typewriters for storage 
and servicing over the summer 
we used to sweat it out when september got close that doesnt 
happen any more this past summer i didnt have a single request 
whitlock said 
im just so darn worn and weary with it now he said 
but closing wasnt so easy 
longtime customers have been rushing to get their machines in 
for repairs before he shuts his doors hes got a backlog of at 
least two dozen repair orders 
manchester a fan of manual typewriters has been coming to 
whitlocks since the 1950s 
ive never known anyone who works on typewriters that can 
match him in any way hes in a class by himself said 
manchester writer in residence at wesleyan university in nearby 
middletown 
whitlock started his repair business in 1934 at the age of 17 
working out of his fathers book store itself a new haven 
institution for years 
ive always liked mechanical challenges and with typewriters 
every one has its own personality and characteristics he said 
whitlock has never worked on electronic typewriters which have 
computer chips he hired an assistant to take care of those 
newfangled machines 
the work has taken its toll he can no longer fully extend his 
right hand which has spent thousands of hours clutching a 
screwdriver 
his dark cluttered store with shelves of vintage jetblack 
manual typewriters has become an anachronism on its block now a 
fashionable home of several eateries a nightclub a copying 
center an art shop and morys the storied yale dining club 
reluctantly whitlock has begun getting rid of his stock he 
recently threw away over 200 cannibalized machines that had served 
as sources of hardtoget parts and has sold most of his antiques 
dozens have also gone home with him 
but there are still some oldies in the store like the midget 
collapsible typewriter weighing less than 7 pounds used by news 
correspondents during world war i and the blueandwhite 
typewriter that his father had smithcorona make for yale students 
in the 1920s 
whitlock refused to entertain any offers to buy the business 
i dont want someone else to have the chance to spoil what 
ive done he said 
</TEXT>
