<DOCNO> AP900809-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
long wary of saddam hussein saudi arabia 
has for the first time turned to the united states for protection 
because of the threat posed by the iraqi invasion of kuwait 
not since the early 1960s when saudi arabia responded to the 
egyptian presence in north yemen has it made such a major military 
commitment to a perceived threat 
knowledgeable saudi officials and arab diplomats based in the 
persian gulf said the saudi leadership has been fearful of saddam 
since he wrested power from ahmed hassan albakr in 1979 
most of saddams neighbors have appeased him to ensure their own 
preservation they said noting saddams decision to wage war on 
iran in 1980 
the saudis tried to placate saddam accepted his promises 
about nonaggression and exerted themselves to arrange an 
understanding between him and the kuwaiti government said one 
arab diplomat speaking on condition his name not be used 
saddam did the same thing with egyptian president hosni 
mubarak who felt insulted when he realized the iraqi leader was 
lying the saudis felt not merely insulted but also threatened 
apart from fighting for their own survival the saudis feel 
indebted to the invaded kuwaitis for harboring them in the latter 
part of the 19th century the arabian peninsula was then part of 
the ottoman empire whose leaders had denied the house of saud 
their throne in riyadh 
but on jan 15 1902 a young warrior prince called abdelaziz 
ibn abdelrahman al saud led 40 desert fighters by camel from 
kuwait to retake riyadh 
aided and encouraged by the benevolent kuwaitis of the alsabah 
family abdelaziz retook riyadh and instituted the monarchy that 
in subsequent decades spread across a vast area covering hidden 
treasures 
the advent of oil transformed both kuwait and saudi arabia 
almost simultaneously into rich countries the two ruling families 
began vying for political distinction jealousies and political 
rivalries often overshadowed their kinship 
but the shock of invasion and the flight of the ruling family 
pushed to the fore the question of survival said one arab 
diplomat the saudis had to choose one of two bitter options 
either to back down and wait for their turn to go down under the 
heavy boots of some neighboring dictator or to resort to the 
americans and defy the iraqis 
the saudis won a denunciation of iraqs invasion from its allies 
on the gulf cooperation council the council said exiled sheik 
jaber alahmed alsabah was the only legitimate ruler of kuwait 
born in the summer of 1981 the gcc groups join saudi arabia 
kuwait the united arab emirates bahrain qatar and oman in a 
military and economic pact 
staterun radio and television stations along with 
governmentguided newspapers in all gcc countries condemned saddam 
as us troops headed to saudi arabia the gcc foreign ministers 
met in jiddah saudi arabia denounced the invasion and called for 
iraqs withdrawal from kuwait 
during the 196267 yemen war the saudis poured massive weapons 
stocks and vast sums of money into yemen and recruited mercenaries 
to evict the egyptian armies of the late president gamal 
abdelnasser 
the net gain for the saudis was the ouster of the forces of 
revolutionary regimes from north yemen 
