a failure to foresee the international fallout that would result 
but the us intelligence profile of saddam also is of a 
risktaker who is not afraid to gamble against long odds concern 
is heightened by the arab leaders profile as one without respect 
for common human values or the normal rules of diplomacy use of 
chemical weapons terrorism and hostagetaking all are 
possibilities they say 
the picture of saddam shows a man with a strange duality tough 
yet fearful inspiring fear in his own people yet also basking in 
a kind of populist veneration from many of the regions arabs 
the portrait is one of a poor orphan who rose to power through 
opportunism and brutality whose antiwestern views were shaped in 
childhood and who now commanding the worlds fourthlargest army 
is trying to deliver on his nationalist dreams 
saddam say intelligence sources and americans who have met with 
him is a ruler without finesse but with keen political instincts 
and welldefined goals 
foremost among those goals the sources say is to become the 
nasser of the 90s the dominant figure in the arab world and 
the chief controller of opec oil 
driving saddam is a devotion to arab political and cultural 
supremacy and a deepseated hatred for israel and for any western 
infringement of his independence particularly from the united 
states and great britain the two countries that have publicly 
committed troops to saudi arabias defense 
but while jealously guarding arab independence saddam also 
covets western technology and education and has sought to modernize 
his country he has been able to work well with the french who 
have supplied many of the weapons that are the basis of iraqs 
military might 
the son of peasants who was orphaned at an early age saddam 
grew up with an uncle in the iraqi town of takrit which was known 
as a hotbed of ferment against the british rule of iraq his uncle 
was arrested for participating in an uprising against the 
government 
he later joined the arab baath socialist party and became 
devoted to the cause of ridding his country of foreign influences 
his rise to power has been facilitated by execution of his 
opponents and he has used chemical weapons against iran and 
against his own kurdish minority 
there is strong evidence that saddam personally shot to death 
one of his cabinet ministers in 1982 after the official said aloud 
at a cabinet meeting that the invasion of iran had been a mistake 
unlike leaders of other moslem countries saddam appears to be a 
purely secular head of state he doesnt seem to value human 
life or to have any moral standards said one congressional 
source who has met with saddam 
he has got certain views that dont appear much amenable to a 
lot of negotiation you didnt come out thinking we can probably 
work out a deal the source said 
saddam frequently states his conviction that there is a 
conspiracy among israel the united states and britain to topple 
him and visitors are left with the impression of someone who is 
insecure saddam who has been the target of assassination 
attempts surrounds himself with military bodyguards 
he wore a gun during a meeting with sen arlen specter rpa 
in january an aide to the senator said 
he relies on terror to maintain his power he is often compared 
to adolf hitler and senate intelligence committee chairman david 
boren dokla called the iraqi security apparatus the most 
effective internal police state in the world 
iraqi citizens are afraid to speak their rulers name said 
boren for fear it will be misunderstood as criticism an offense 
that is punishable by execution 
his sense of face and dignity is extremely important said 
another us analyst he governs by ruthlessness and fear and 
awe if he is thought to lose face thats losing a good half of 
his capacity 
