in a gesture to a friendly and important 
customer mexico will send an additional 100000 barrels of oil a 
day to the united states to help ease shortages caused by the 
embargo imposed against iraq and kuwait 
the mexican commitment scheduled to last two months is 
expected to restore about 15 percent of the more than 700000 
barrels a day the united states is no longer receiving as a result 
of the embargo 
the mexican decision was announced wednesday by foreign 
secretary fernando solana who headed his countrys delegation to a 
daylong meeting of mexican and american officials convened to 
discuss crossborder issues 
saudi arabia and venezuela also announced plans wednesday to 
increase oil production 
while the mexican move could ease concerns about domestic 
supplies in this country it also will provide added cash to 
mexico with a bonus resulting from the higher prices caused by the 
persian gulf crisis 
treasury secretary nicholas brady praised the mexican action 
saying it exemplifies the spirit of relations between the two 
countries 
this aid by mexico is much appreciated at this time brady 
said solana said he felt it was necessary to meet the needs of 
an important and friendly customer 
total us oil imports average an estimated 4 million barrels a 
day solana indicated that the mexican increase would have been 
higher but that oil production in mexico is running virtually at 
capacity 
mexico exports about half of its 25 million barrel daily 
production of oil 
