<TEXT>
twenty years ago saudi arabia depended 
on the annual moslem pilgrimage to mecca for a significant portion 
of its revenue 
the unprecedented oil wealth accumulated since then has helped 
it build a modern state and army but balancing traditional islamic 
political and social laws with the dizzying speed of development 
has always made the royal family feel vulnerable 
the name saudi arabia is almost synonymous with oil the 
estimated 255 billion barrels of oil lying beneath its deserts 
represent a quarter of known world reserves 
the jump in prices in the 1970s from a few dollars to more than 
40 per barrel brought staggering wealth saudi citizens are 
believed to have 200 billion in western banks the government has 
about 70 billion in financial reserves down from 130 billion a 
decade ago due to low oil prices in the late 1980s 
spending has been prolific with the annual budgets at about 35 
billion defense spending in the projected 1990 budget was 138 
billion about 40 percent of the total the alsaud rulers spent 
just 100 million on defense in 1971 fearful of spawning a 
competing power 
the vast growth in the neighboring armed forces of iraq iran 
and israel as well as the value of the oil reserves changed that 
attitude 
we are a very appealing piece of cake former oil minister 
ahmed zaki yamani once said 
geographically saudi arabia is a massive desert except for the 
mountainous areas near the red sea at roughly 873000 square 
miles it is about onethird the size of the united states 
no formal census statistics exist but the population is 
estimated at about 14 million with more than 45 million 
foreigners 
the local populaton is overwhelming sunni moslem there is a 
shiite minority in the eastern oilproducing province often 
suspected of harboring sympathies for the islamic revolution in 
largely shiite iran 
islam pervades the social political legal and cultural system 
of saudi arabia it was shaped by wahhabism named after an 
18thcentury puritan he sought to maintain islam as it existed 
when the prophet mohammed founded the faith in mecca in the 7th 
century 
women and men are strictly separated in public women are 
veiled have a separate education system and are not allowed to 
drive 
the modern state dates only to 1932 when the king known in the 
west as ibn saud unified a collection of tribal provinces the 
tribe numbers about 4000 princes the few hundred directly 
involved in running the country control all significant posts 
king fahd is head of state commander of chief of the armed 
forces and prime minister his crown prince is his halfbrother 
prince abdullah head of the national guard 
next in line is defense minister prince sultan a full brother 
of fahd interior minister prince naif is a full brother as is the 
governor of riyadh prince salman 
all nine provincial governors are royals 
other prominent family members include foreign minister prince 
saud alfeisal a son of the late king feisal and nephew to fahd 
the ambassador to the united states prince bandar ibn sultan is 
son of the defense minister 
differences rarely spill into public unless on the scale of the 
early 1960s fight to get the incompetent king saud off the throne 
decisionmaking is done by consulting the princes and other 
powerful tribes each leader confers with the people through a 
majlis or audiences that any saudi male has the right to attend 
the system builds consensus but is painfully slow thus the 
saudi government has long relied on the united states to provide 
backup to its 60000man army in times of crisis 
thousands of us military advisers live in saudi arabia to help 
with training 
saudi arabia helped insulate the world economy from major oil 
supply interruptions by increasing production at crisis periods 
such as the 1979 revolution in iran 
but ussaudi relations have been rocky due to strong 
israeliamerican ties 
the saudi arabian kings most prestigious title is guardian of 
the two holy cities mecca and medina the treasury once depended 
totally on what moslem pilgrims spent on their annual visit 
as long as the third holiest city jerusalem remains under 
israeli control detractors like iran can challenge the alsaud 
role as guardians of the faith 
saudi arabia has always avoided allowing us forces openly into 
the country out of fear their presence would help an internal 
opposition jell 
an air base near dhahran was closed in 1962 
the united states has been sensitive to the need for saudi 
arabia to keep its distance 
we must continue to recognize that preserving saudi arabias 
own stability requires the government to maintain a posture of 
independence secretary of state alexander haig said during one 
of the bruising congressional battles saudi arabia went through to 
acquire sophisticated us weapons the israeli lobby in congress 
always sought to block the sales 
</TEXT>
