<TEXT>
the justice department filed suit under the 
voting rights act today challenging georgias runoff election 
system that requires candidates to receive a majority of the vote 
to win an election 
the law similar to legislation in eight other southern states 
gives white candidates an extraordinary power said john r 
dunne assistant us attorney general for civil rights 
the law has stymied black candidates who may win the most votes 
in a threeway race with two white candidates but cant gain a 
majority in the ensuing twoway runoff 
dunne said the law has had a demonstratively chilling effect 
on the intent and willingness of blacks to become candidates for 
office across the south 
the other states with similar runoff systems are alabama 
arkansas florida louisiana oklahoma mississippi south 
carolina and texas 
georgias majority vote law requires a runoff election in every 
state local and federal election in which a candidate does not 
receive a majority of the vote 
the suit filed in atlanta is the first challenge of a majority 
vote runoff system brought by the justice department under the 1965 
voting rights act 
perry michael assistant state attorney general said georgia 
officials only learned of the suit today and would not comment 
until they have reviewed it 
dunne said the lawsuit was similar to one filed earlier in 
georgia by state rep tyrone brooks but unlike the brooks suit he 
said the justice department action does not seek to invalidate the 
entire runoff law 
dunne said the justice suit would challenge only those elections 
in which the majority vote requirement has been used to dilute the 
voting strength of minorities that would include all statewide 
elections and many local elections where blacks comprise a majority 
of the voting population but have been unable to elect black 
candidates 
although 24 percent of georgias voting age population is black 
dunne said blacks hold fewer than 10 percent of elected offices in 
the state and most of those are at the local level 
the higher the office and the broader the constituency the 
smaller the number of black elected officials he said 
dunne said the department waited until after georgias tuesday 
runoff election in the democratic primary for governor to file the 
suit so the action could not be interpreted as a challenge to those 
results 
</TEXT>
