charlotte burnett acknowledges her transfer 
three years ago to head a bank in watts was not exactly the career 
move she had in mind 
after all for many watts is the definition of urban blight and 
racial unrest the community after which the watts riot of 25 years 
ago was named california federals watts branch is on 103rd 
street once known as charcoal alley 
but running the only bank in the los angeles community of watts 
proved a rewarding experience and greatly changed burnetts view of 
the community and its potential for the future 
what i have found is that what i see on television and in the 
newspaper about the community is basically not very true or the 
whole picture she said i see a difference i always see the 
negative in the media i see the positive here 
burnett is among a dedicated core of business people and 
community activists working to turn watts around 
from her vantage point as a bank vice president burnett sees 
the other side of watts the working people the families and 
retirees who overwhelmingly outnumber the drug dealers and school 
dropouts who always seem to make the news 
many of the people in watts have lived there for 40 or more 
years in homes from the 1940s with neat lawns and freshly painted 
fences on treelined streets many blocks away from the housing 
projects and vacant lots 
the calfed branch which opened in 1970 symbolizes for many 
residents watts rebound from the riot of 1965 and offers an 
example of where the community can go 
the branch employs 13 people 10 of them from watts and handles 
a wide variety of services from checking to mutual funds 
as a local business person burnett often has duties outside the 
office from giving investment seminars to working on community 
advisory programs 
i see people who have pride in their community an attitude 
of were going to make this work its going to be as good a 
community as any other community she said but most important 
thing is i see families the pictures they media never show of 
the mother the father and the children i see it every day 
