weak commercial real estate markets have 
spread from the northeast and southwest to the midwest and even the 
booming west coast a federal reserve board member said thursday 
real estate problems have been most pronounced in new england 
john p laware told the house banking committee but weakness now 
exists along much of the east coast 
market conditions in some midwestern cities have also begun to 
show a marked loss of strength and even the western states of 
california oregon and washington long the beneficiaries of strong 
real estate markets have begun to report increased office vacancy 
rates in at least some areas he said 
as a result the number of delinquent real estate loans at 
commercial banks are mounting up 37 percent in 1989 and 8 percent 
to 32 billion in the first three months of 1990 he said 
however laware and comptroller of the currency robert l 
clarke whose office oversees nationally chartered banks said 
regulators were on top of the trend and insisting on sound lending 
standards 
the comptrollers office has been sounding the alarm on real 
estate lending for the past three years clarke said 
members of the committee reacted skeptically likening the 
deterioration in bank profits and the regulators reactions to the 
early phases of the savings and loan mess 
