swiss red cross workers would be freed within 24 hours 
there was no explanation from the kidnappers for the delay in 
freeing erriquez 
before being abducted both men worked as orthopedic technicians 
at a red cross hospital in the southern lebanese port of sidon 
the swiss foreign minister told swiss tv he was confident 
christens release was a signal for the next liberation 
we are happy that emanuel is free but we are also concerned 
that elio is still a captive christens mother marianne 
christen said in a separate television interview 
she said she was shocked earlier when she saw a photo of her son 
released by the kidnappers shortly before he was freed she said he 
seemed thin and has such a sad look 
a swiss embassy staff member in damascus claudine zbinden said 
christen had lost about 30 pounds but he is in relative good 
shape if one may say so ms zbinden said thursday in a 
telephone interview 
both the swiss foreign ministry and the genevaheadquartered 
international committee of the red cross denied any deal was made 
with the kidnappers to win the hostages release 
in their statement tuesday the palestine revolutionary squads 
said they decided to free the two swiss captives after we 
acquired guarantees that our demands will be met 
erriquezs brother antoine said he was convinced there had been 
a deal between the kidnappers and swiss officials 
they had to make a concession even if they deny it he 
said but it is also possible that the terrorists after 
releasing one hostage are now waiting whether all of their demands 
are being met before also freeing my brother 
in paris the french foreign ministry said the release may have 
been a result of frances decision last month to pardon anis 
naccache and four other members of a proiranian assassination team 
a ministry spokesman said france was informed immediately after 
naccaches release july 27 that iran would pursue efforts to free 
hostages held in lebanon and that two europeans would be freed soon 
christens release brought to 15 the number of foreigners held 
hostage in lebanon 
the longest held is terry anderson 42 chief middle east 
correspondent of the associated press he was kidnapped march 16 
1985 
