after six weeks of testimony the jury in the 
central park jogger case began deliberations thursday weighing the 
charges against three teenagers in one of the citys most infamous 
crimes 
yusef salaam 16 raymond santana 15 and antron mccray 16 
are charged with attempted murder rape sexual abuse riot 
assault and robbery in attacks on the woman and on two male joggers 
during a rampage on april 19 1989 
the woman was dragged into the woods gangraped bashed with a 
brick and a pipe and left to die in a pool of blood after going 
into the park for her nightly run the brutality of the attack and 
her surprising recovery caught the attention of the city and the 
nation 
defense lawyers summed up tuesday with one attorney suggesting 
the victim was not gangraped and another accusing detectives of 
lying about how incriminating statements were obtained from the 
three defendants 
the three were tried as adults but if convicted would be 
sentenced as juveniles limiting the length of any prison terms 
videotaped statements by mccray and santana were shown during 
the trial and again during the closing argument wednesday 
the jury thursday requested the written statements the three 
defendants gave police the defense has charged the statements were 
coerced from the defendants 
the panel also asked the judge about the admissibility of any 
statement made by a minor without a parent or guardian present 
the fact that a parent was not present during the questioning 
of a juvenile does not automatically mean the statement is 
involuntary justice thomas galligan told the jurors 
the 30yearold jogger is back at work as a vice president at 
salomon brothers investment bankers in a dramatic appearance at 
the trial she testified that she still suffers from impaired 
sight balance and smell as a result of the attack 
the fact that she could even come to this courtroom is a 
miracle prosecutor elizabeth lederer said 
