<TEXT>
farmers are looking at a potential 1990 corn 
harvest of 785 billion bushels up 4 percent from last year the 
agriculture department said thursday 
at 785 billion bushels this falls harvest would be the 
largest since 825 billion bushels in 1986 the record was the 1985 
crop of nearly 89 billion bushels 
dry conditions in the southeastern states have reduced yields 
in most areas from the record levels of 1989 said the 
departments agricultural statistics board 
but the report added that late plantings in the corn belt have 
been offset by excellent growing conditions in july 
farmers harvested 753 billion bushels in 1989 and the 
department a month ago projected this years output might be 785 
billion bushels based on yield trends and normal weather 
thursdays figures were the first of the season by usda based on 
yield estimates and surveys reflecting conditions as of aug 1 
corn yields were estimated at 1177 bushels per acre harvested 
compared with 1162 last year the record was 1194 bushels in 1987 
as livestock feed corn is the largest and most important us 
farm crop it is an essential ingredient for the production of 
meat poultry and dairy products 
consumer food prices which rose an average of 58 percent in 
1989 the sharpest yeartoyear increase since 1981 are expected 
to climb 6 percent or more in 1990 
soybean production a source of highprotein meal and vegetable 
oil was estimated at 184 billion bushels down 5 percent from 
last years harvest of 193 billion bushels 
cotton production was indicated at 149 million bales up 22 
percent from last years output of 122 million bales 
total wheat output was estimated at 271 billion bushels up 33 
percent from the 1989 harvest and fractionally more than indicated 
in july 
the departments allcrops production index was reported at 111 
percent of its 1977 average used for comparison that is the 
highest reading since the index averaged 116 percent in 1985 
last year although crop production rebounded sharply from the 
1988 drought total output averaged only 106 percent the record 
was 117 percent in 1981 and 1982 
in a related report on supply and demand for major commodities 
analysts said total corn use in the 199091 marketing year which 
begins sept 1 is expected to be about 7975 billion bushels 
including domestic and export requirements 
with demand exceeding 1990 corn production that will mean a 
further drawdown of us stockpiles to about 12 billion bushels 
left over by sept 1 1991 down from inventories estimated at 133 
billion bushels at the beginning of the marketing year this sept 1 
but that represents only a slight dip in the us corn 
stockpile compared to last seasons decline when it plummeted 
from 426 billion bushels on sept 1 1988 to 193 billion bushels 
on hand last sept 1 
the report said us corn prices may average in the range of 
235 to 275 per bushel in the 199091 marketing year compared 
with 238 forecast for the current season 
soybean prices at the farm were forecast at 550 to 7 per 
bushel in 199091 compared with 570 in the last marketing year 
the report said farm prices of wheat may average 265 to 305 
per bushel compared with 372 the last two marketing years 
other 1990 crop estimates based on aug 1 indications compared 
with 1989 output included 
sorghum 5468 million bushels and an average yield of 591 
bushels per acre compared with 6179 million and 554 in 1989 
rice 1581 million hundredweight and a yield of 5611 pounds 
per acre compared with 1545 million and 5749 
peanuts 418 billion pounds and a yield of 2449 pounds per 
acre compared with 399 billion and 2426 
tobacco 152 billion pounds and a yield of 2102 pounds per 
acre compared with 137 billion and 2016 
sugar beets 281 million tons and a yield of 204 tons per 
acre compared with 251 million and 194 
sugar cane 249 million tons and a yield of 351 tons per 
acre compared with 294 million and 345 
