<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency said 
thursday it will require an 80 percent reduction of sulfur in 
diesel fuel starting oct 1 1993 
the new requirement is expected to add from 18 to 23 cents per 
gallon to the cost of the fuel the agency said 
diesel exhaust has been identified as a potential cause of 
cancer epa administrator william k reilly said the sulfur 
reduction requirement and new standards to reduce particulates 
beginning in 1991 will virtually eliminate the black smoke from 
diesel tailpipes cutting particulates by 90 percent 
the most impact will be felt in urban areas where pollution is 
heaviest and the most people are exposed reilly said in a 
statement 
however the private environmental defense fund said the epa 
plan doesnt go far enough because it does not reduce aromatics 
chemicals the defense fund says are responsible for almost half the 
particulate emissions in some cities 
the epa said it will control aromatics at about current 
levels by requiring a performance rating for diesel fuel or an 
optional maximum aromatics content standard 
that plan doesnt take advantage of a major strategy to help 
clean up polluted cities thats relatively cost effective and 
cleans up emissions from every vehicle on the road that burns 
diesel said bob yuhnke a senior attorney with the defense fund 
he said epas steps will result in a 15 to 20 percent reduction 
in particulate emissions from diesel fuel compared to a 35 to 40 
percent reduction in california which has reduced both sulfur and 
aromatics 
the new epa sulfur rule is based on a 1988 proposal developed 
jointly by the dieselengine manufacturing and petroleum refining 
industries 
it requires refiners to reduce the sulfur content of diesel fuel 
used on the road from 25 percent by weight to 05 percent 
cost to refiners is expected to range from 380 million to 910 
million in 1995 and 540 million to 13 billion by 2010 
those costs will be at least partially offset for the consumer 
by cheaper emission control devices fuel savings from catalytic 
devices and possibly less wear on the engine epa said 
small refiners have until 1995 to phase in the new standards as 
they install equipment needed to remove the sulfur they will have 
to meet interim standards during that period 
from 1993 to 1995 fuel produced under the interim standards 
will be sold only for pre1994 engine equipped vehicles or to 
offhighway markets the epa said that is in order to protect 1994 
and later modelyear engine designs that will require only 
lowsulfur fuel 
the sulfur reductions are expected to help diesel engine 
manufacturers meet tighter particulate exhaust standards that will 
take effect in 1991 and 1994 the epa said the lower level of 
sulfur will reduce direct emissions of sulfate particulates and 
also reduce secondary formation of particulates in the atmosphere 
by 1995 particulates are projected to be down by 196000 tons a 
year sulfur dioxide levels should decrease by 580000 tons per 
year the agency said 
</TEXT>
