secretary of state james a baker iii received 
pledges wednesday from turkey that its air bases could be used as 
staging areas for us military strikes against iraq in the event 
of war 
baker then flew to nato headquarters in brussels seeking a 
reaffirmation the allies would rush to turkeys defense if iraq 
attacked its neighbor 
bakers meetings in ankara with president turgut ozal and other 
turkish officials will expand military and intelligence cooperation 
with the frontline state which fears iraqi intimidation for 
effectively shutting down two oil pipelines and freezing trade with 
baghdad 
us and western diplomats said the turks took those steps 
reluctantly and that some 60000 turkish workers in iraq could be 
vulnerable as the usorganized economic boycott tightens 
turkey which stands to lose an estimated 3 billion a year in 
commerce with iraq received through baker an offer of some 
compensation from the oilrich kuwaiti royal family that was 
overthrown in the iraqi invasion 
for his part baker promised the united states would back turkey 
in its request for development loans from the world bank and would 
provide credits for turkey to import industrial machinery 
also an administration official said baker wrote a letter to 
the european community supporting turkeys application for 
membership in the 12nation european community 
as baker left ankara after a ninehour visit he was reluctant 
to discuss his request for permission to use an air base near the 
southern city of adana or smaller posts as a staging area in the 
event of a us attack on iraq 
the united states has a military force of 2400 at the 
turkishoperated training facility and rotates up to two dozen 
f111 bombers there similar to the planes used in a 1986 raid 
against libya 
turkey is also strategically located for gathering intelligence 
on the soviet union iraq and other middle eastern countries 
the use for which we can utilize those bases is well 
understood baker said im not going to speculate about 
possible hypotheticals 
