security forces shot and killed three rioters 
thursday during unrest over austerity measures that sent the cost 
of food soaring by 300 percent or more 
soldiers patrolled the capital city of lima in armored cars 
brandishing automatic weapons and wearing ski masks for fear of 
retribution from rioters the violence broke out after prime 
minister juan hurtado miller announced economic austerity measures 
wednesday night in a bid to ease the worst economic crisis in 
perus history on thursday the government announced a new 
measure saying it has decided to float perus currency the inti 
the price of gasoline a government monopoly jumped from 7 
cents a gallon to more than 2 private bus lines halted runs 
thursday stranding thousands of people commuters fought one 
another for room in the back of pickup trucks 
police reported looting in a dozen small street markets in 
shantytowns that ring lima 
police and soldiers opened fire and killed a man and a woman 
among about 130 protesters who were burning rubber tires to block a 
highway 10 miles east of lima 
in ancon a beach town 25 miles north of lima a peruvian marine 
shot to death a man involved in a fight with other shoppers at a 
municipal food market 
tension in the capital had mounted in the days leading up to 
hurtados announcement many shops doubled their prices even before 
his address bread noodles beans sugar cooking oil and milk 
disappeared from store shelves 
the emergency economic package included elimination of subsidies 
to cut a huge budget deficit which hurtado blamed for perus 3000 
percent annual inflation 
the decision to let the currency float means its value will be 
determined by supply and demand the subsidized dollar cost only 
about onesixth of the freemarket dollar in the final days of the 
previous government of president alan garcia 
perus inti is expected to quickly fall on the open market 
lowering the price of the countrys exports on the world market 
however the move will bring much higher prices for imported goods 
the government must exercise leadership even if it means a 
loss of its popularity said hurtado who also is economy 
minister in the new centrist government of president alberto 
fujimori 
fujimoris predecessor garcia was a populist who spent the 
countrys last dollar reserves before leaving office july 28 
what we are suffering today was originated by a government 
that treated us all like guinea pigs to try out its wonderful 
theory that a nation can indiscriminately increase its deficit by 
printing money without affecting prices hurtado said in a 
television address 
weighed down by hyperinflation perus economy shrank 20 percent 
in the last two years four of five people are out of work 
starting now hurtado said perus new government would not 
spend more than it receives in tax revenues he said public 
services must charge enough to cover their costs 
the emergency package also includes special taxes on the rich 
reduction of import duties to open up the economy to competition 
from foreign goods and a wage bonus for workers equivalent to 
their july pay 
some observers have suggested fujimori will have to use the army 
to keep order in the face of the harsh economic measures he named 
two army generals to head the defense ministry and the interior 
ministry which controls the police forces 
most public markets in the capital were closed thursday troops 
were sent to huancayo a major commercial center 120 miles from 
lima to prevent looting shops stayed closed in arequipa perus 
secondbiggest city 465 miles southeast of the capital 
the dollar doubled in value on limas parallel street market 
jumping from 200000 intis to 400000 in three days on thursday it 
fell back to about 350000 intis 
during a brief visit wednesday vice president dan quayle said 
the united states supported fujimoris austerity measures and 
expressed confidence the reforms would put this country back on 
the road to economic recovery 
he said the bush administration was seeking congressional 
approval for 160 million in military and economic aid for peru in 
1991 
</TEXT>
