<TEXT>
americans strongly support president bushs 
decision to send troops to saudi arabia even though most believe 
the united states is headed toward war with iraq according to 
polls released thursday 
survey respondents also supported the embargo of iraqi oil and 
many said they would accept higher gasoline prices to make it work 
but most blamed last weeks jumps in gasoline prices on oil company 
greed not the embargo 
iraq invaded neighboring kuwait last week and annexed it 
wednesday bush dispatched us troops to deter an iraqi attack on 
saudi arabia explaining his move in a televised address to the 
nation wednesday 
usa today in a survey of 610 people wednesday found that 81 
percent supported sending troops to saudi arabia cbs news 
surveying 773 people tuesday and wednesday found 63 percent 
approval and a poll of 769 people wednesday by abc news and the 
washington post found 74 percent support 
however the cbs poll indicated military action was not 
americans first choice asked the best response to iraq 42 
percent said hold off for the time being and 35 percent favored 
using diplomatic and economic weapons just 13 percent favored 
military force the rest favored some combination or were unsure 
the bottom line is basically this is a popular action said 
kathleen a frankovic pollster for cbs while there may be 
clouds over the horizon right now theyre still in the distance 
polls conducted on breaking news events tend to measure visceral 
reactions and the surveys found immediate fears of war were high 
seventythree percent in the usa today poll said us forces are 
likely to end up in combat against iraqi forces 
similarly 66 percent in the cbs poll called it likely that the 
situation in the middle east will lead to an extended war involving 
the united states twentytwo percent called that very likely 
44 percent somewhat likely 
in the usa today and cbs surveys 49 percent favored using us 
troops to try to force iraq out of kuwait support for economic and 
political sanctions was considerably higher 
in the abcpost survey 69 percent favored a naval blockade of 
iraq but strong majorities opposed us military strikes against 
iraq 
on the oil embargo 68 percent told cbs it was a good idea even 
if it meant higher prices and 50 percent said they would support 
the embargo even if it made gasoline prices reach 2 per gallon 
fortynine percent told usa today they would pay an additional 50 
cents or more per gallon to make the embargo work 
but most said the embargo was not the culprit in recent price 
increases eightyseven percent in the abcpost poll and 84 percent 
in the cbs poll said gasoline companies were using the crisis as an 
excuse to raise prices 
the telephone surveys had error margins of plus or minus four 
percentage points 
