<TEXT>
in a ruling described as the largest such 
award in maritime history a japanese shipping company was ordered 
to pay 21 underpaid filipino sailors 32 million in back wages and 
punitive damages 
us district judge jack tanner said the delica shipping co 
which admitted underpaying the mv pine forests sailors on voyages 
between japan and the united states had acted in a flagrant 
malicious indifferent and unconscionable manner 
in his ruling monday tanner awarded the sailors 150000 in 
back pay 15 million in compensatory and penalty wages and 17 
million in punitive damages 
it was by far the largest wage award in maritime history said 
jim lafferty director of the new yorkbased center for seafarers 
rights the previous highest award was 26 million he said 
the vanuaturegistered pine forest carries douglas fir logs from 
weyerhaeuser co docks in tacoma and longview to ports in japan 
the seamen were recruited last year with employment contracts 
that left blank a space indicating their wages and later signed 
shipping articles promising them higher wages under a collective 
agreement with the worldwide international transport workers 
federation tanner said 
the sailors never got the higher pay 
us law gives federal courts jurisdiction over wage cases 
involving foreign vessels and crews whose voyages end in us 
waters 
