<TEXT>
herman leonards admiration for jazz and his 
fascination with the people who play it led him to spend many late 
nights photographing the musicians in dark and smoky clubs 
i love to photograph interesting people musicians artists 
writers leonard said i get to know them and photograph them 
as i see them this is my passion 
the results of that passion are the 45 photos capturing jazz 
greats such as duke ellington dizzy gillespie billie holiday and 
charlie parker now touring the country in leonards images of 
jazz exhibit 
the exhibit will be in chicago at the catherine edelman gallery 
until aug 18 on the fourth stop of a 10gallery us tour the 
photos also will be shown in seven cities in europe 
leonards photos capture the 1940s and 50s jazz scene his 
backlighting technique plays light off the skin of many of the 
musicians highlighting the sweat on their foreheads an occasional 
smile of joy and frequent frowns of concentration 
i wanted to get images that for me personally were 
representative of the atmosphere leonard said in an interview 
leonard took the pictures in clubs around the world from new 
york to paris to los angeles but it wasnt until the 1980s when 
he was living in paris and a french publisher approached him about 
putting together a book of his jazz photos that he pulled them out 
after almost 20 years of neglect 
id put them in a cardboard box and stuck them under the 
bed said leonard whose photos were compiled into the 1985 book 
the eye of jazz 
the 67yearold photographer said age plays a big part in the 
reaction people have to his photo exhibit 
for the grayhaired guys it kind of revives a memory 
leonard said its different for the teenagers theyve heard 
and loved the music and it gives them a chance to feel what it was 
like to be there 
the exhibit has attracted everyone from jazz buffs to parents 
who try to explain who the musicians are to their small children 
said catherine edelman owner of the chicago gallery she added 
that leonards photos have such a mass appeal they are bringing a 
new audience into her gallery 
jazz crosses barriers its a concept they respect edelman 
said 
but nothing really prepared me for the amount of love coming 
out of people she said its not just dealing with fine art 
people go up to each other and ask hey have you ever seen dizzy 
play 
