<TEXT>
leaders of all three countries have approved 
the integration of singapore with parts of indonesia and malaysia 
in a compact economic growth triangle designed to attract 
foreign capital 
the idea is to present singapore the southern tip of peninsular 
malaysia and several nearby indonesian islands as a single 
investment center not separate areas competing for capital 
no formal treaty or europeanstyle common market is planned 
officials said but cooperation would mean uniform standards of 
economic management and safeguards for investors in individual 
projects 
deputy prime minister goh chok tong of singapore proposed the 
idea in december his affluent citystate would seem at first 
glance to gain more than its poorer neighbors from such an 
arrangement 
singapore has only 27 million people and no hinterland its 
growth is limited by insufficient labor water and room to expand 
goh suggested the triangle could boom in the 1990s by combining 
the land labor water and gas of malaysias johor state and 
indonesias batam island with the managerial talent available in 
singapore 
as an added attraction the area could be promoted as a sort of 
caribbean tourist playground goh said with beach resorts on 
johor and batam and singapore for shopping 
president suharto of indonesia and malaysias prime minister 
mohamad mahathir endorsed the idea in june when suharto visited 
kuala lumpur 
we agreed that we should work together mahathir told 
reporters it will be beneficial for all three of us we can 
benefit from the prosperity and spending power of singapore and the 
spillover effect of its tourism industry 
singapore had 48 million tourists last year 
government and private planning groups were set up last year 
between johor and singapore and earlier this year between 
indonesia and singapore to expand cooperation and streamline 
customs procedures 
as operating costs in singapore soared in recent years many 
manufacturing firms shifted laborintensive operations to johor 
which is linked to singapore by a causeway that carries a highway 
railroad and water pipeline 
another bridge is planned electronic components and other goods 
shipped into johor and later exported are not taxed 
with costs increasing in johor singapore manufacturers have set 
their sights on batam island a dutyfree zone only 12 miles to the 
southeast by ferry 
industrialists estimate the labor cost in johor is about half 
that of singapore and in batam only half that of johor 
two stateowned singapore companies announced in january they 
would put 220 million into a joint venture with an indonesian firm 
to build an industrial park mainly for computer assembly plants 
the promoters said it would employ 40000 people when completed in 
five years 
politically the triangle could help forge closer ties between 
singapore most of whose people are ethnic chinese and its big 
malay neighbors which experienced antichinese bloodshed in the 
1960s 
prime minister lee kuan yew said the joint planning showed 
singapores neighbors realized they had more to gain by plugging 
into the citystates success than by trying to go it alone goh is 
scheduled to replace lee in november 
not everyone is so confident muhyiddin yassin head of the 
johor government likes the idea in principle but insists his state 
be a full partner not a mere supplier of primary resources 
tosrin jarvanthi a johor state legislator questioned 
singapores sincerity we have to examine the proposal very 
closely to make sure that we will not lose out in future 
bj habibie an indonesian government minister who oversees 
batams industrial development praised the triangle concept but 
said singapore probably stood to gain more than jakarta 
frans seda a former indonesian finance minister saw great 
benefits for singapore some gain for batam and uncertainty for the 
rest of indonesia 
the straits times took note of such sentiments in an editorial 
the underlying fear no doubt is that singapore would have not 
have come out so enthusiastically and at such high level in favor 
of the idea if it did not stand to benefit disproportionately from 
it 
the government may thus have no choice but to maintain a 
watchful eye over the whole project to ensure that singaporeans 
venturing to johor and riau batam are good envoys as well as good 
businessmen 
</TEXT>
