<TEXT>
thirty soviet american and polish teachers 
spent two weeks discussing educational alchemy how to turn the 
leaden classrooms of preperestroika eastern europe into golden 
laboratories of democracy 
they talked about ways teachers can run their classrooms 
democratically and how students could be taught skills and 
attitudes needed in a democracy and they basked in the changes 
brought on by soviet leader mikhail gorbachev 
gorbachev himself has said we are a people who dont know 
how to carry on a discussion we are used to giving orders said 
alan shapiro director of the soviet education project of educators 
for social responsibility which cosponsored the gathering here 
whats missing is the culture of democracy people are not 
really accustomed to what the democratic process means how long it 
takes authoritarianism can be much more efficient 
schools reflected that authoritarianism 
classes have been conducted more like a catechism the teacher 
asks the question and the student must give the right answer you 
could go through a lot of soviet classrooms and never hear a 
student ask a question he said 
at one point in the workshop which ended last weekend the 
teachers sat in a circle trying to name the worlds most populous 
countries with give and take they came up with the answers 
such a freewheeling exercise as common in american classrooms 
as chalk was formerly unheardof in polish and soviet classrooms 
in the 1960s and 1970s i may have had that but it would have 
been risky said valentina mitina who taught for 22 years and is 
now a researcher in comparative education at moscows academy of 
pedagogical sciences 
the flint meeting the third sponsored by the academy soviet 
educators for peace and mutual understanding and educators for 
social responsibility based in cambridge mass took place at a 
time of rapidly increasing contacts between us and eastern 
european educators 
the americans want to help us students appreciate the 
historical significance of changes in eastern europe the europeans 
are looking to america for lessons in how to teach democratic 
concepts and foster an inquiring attitude among students accustomed 
to accepting lessons unquestioningly 
the american federation of teachers has been particularly active 
in fostering such contacts through the international federation of 
free teachers unions based in the netherlands the union has been 
working with emerging free teacher unions in czechoslovakia 
poland bulgaria romania and hungary 
american universities have also been increasing their east bloc 
ties clemson university announced plans in july to set up an mba 
program in moscow the university of michigan announced in june it 
is establishing a center for social research in warsaw poland 
changes do not come easily educators who want to shed 
dictatorial ways often face opposition from parents and students 
said alexander bannov a school principal in the siberian town of 
novosibirsk 
they are afraid to have choices and participate in 
decisionmaking because they dont want to take responsibility for 
poor decisions he said in the old days they could blame the 
leaders 
people are just not prepared for that the process of 
preparing our people to live in a democracy is a very difficult 
pedagogical problem 
if we just declare a democracy nothing happens it can lead 
to anarchy it democracy must be in every minute in every 
detail we should not teach about democracy we should live 
democracy he said 
gennady belyaev a moscow teacher is helping students write a 
peace dictionary in which children develop their own definitions 
for words such as trust and understanding 
the class openly discusses the use of soviet weapons by the 
iraqis on the kurds for example as it shatters the assumption 
that everything done by the soviet union automatically is good 
we try to call a spade a spade he said he confessed his 
main problem is freeing students from the fear of repercussions for 
expressing their views 
no one is going to go to the headmaster and report them he 
said 
but ruth bowman executive director of the cambridge group said 
there are unexpected similarities between american and soviet 
students and american teachers also are searching for ways to 
teach citizenship 
what ive learned from being with the soviets is we seem to 
have very common problems bowman said 
this surprised me they use the word apathy quite a bit one 
of the soviet educators said her students want to be spoonfed they 
dont want to work for their learning were asking the same kind 
of questions 
that made the institute a twoway exchange rather than a 
seminar taught by americans for soviets she said 
one specific thing i have learned is we are not as democratic 
as we think we are and they are not as undemocratic as we think 
they are said arthur marquardt an adrian mich high school 
teacher 
</TEXT>
