<TEXT>
for years philadelphia schools have offered students a chance 
to study latin as early as fourth grade but this fall fewer kids 
will learn their amo amas amats a tight budget has forced 
the layoff of six out of 26 itinerant latin teachers 
an awful lot of them wont even finish high school and the 
only language they are exposed to is street language this is the 
one opportunity they have to get a little something beyond 
thatsaid one laidoff latin teacher h michael dunn 
many such cuts affecting both innovative programs and 
daytoday operations await bigcity districts across the country 
this fall a check by the associated press found that districts 
from philadelphia boston and new york to dade county fla and 
los angeles face the worst fiscal problems since the mid70s 
its going to be tough to innovate when youre trying to 
survive said james fleming associate superintendent of dade 
county schools a district that gained national notice for school 
reforms but now faces a 108 million deficit that will likely lead 
to more crowded classes 
with a possible recession looming and worsening state finances 
putting a squeeze on school budgets bigcity school officials 
everywhere are bracing for teacher hiring freezes layoffs and 
larger classes 
its a very bleak fall said jewell gould research director 
of the american federation of teachers 
he and others believe next spring could bring even worse news 
when districts customarily send out layoff notices 
one leading reformer called this falls cutbacks fresh evidence 
that political leaders give more lip service than resources to 
school improvement 
if snow is piling up in city streets you get a greater sense 
of emergency than if half the kids drop out of school year after 
year said ernest l boyer president of the carnegie foundation 
for the advancement of teaching 
on the one hand we say education is at the center of what we 
hope for and dream about and we almost get maudlin about it but 
then if something happens it gets put off as kid stuff he 
said 
this is easily the worst fiscal crisis i have seen in the last 
20 years said fleming of dade county 
state funding fell 44 million less than expected said dade 
county school spokesman andy gollan its already meant elimination 
of a merit schools program where schools devised innovative 
programs to help students achieve educational goals 
philadelphia anticipating deficits of 68 million for fiscal 
year 199192 170 million in 1993 and 275 million in 1994 has 
put on hold reforms including fullday kindergartens lengthening 
the school day and year and more classroom computers 
its come to a period where we have to make hard choices 
which are not necessarily popular choices said leontine d 
scott associate superintendent 
in boston a 397 million budget approved last week is 64 
million lower than last years cuts include 100 fewer nontenured 
teachers fewer school police reduced extracurricular and 
afterschool programs less funding for a cityfinanced parent 
organization and reductions in a private industry council that 
provides jobs for highschool students 
