forced extensive administrative cuts the crisis worsened last week 
when gov george deukmejian announced he was withholding 465 
million in school funds statewide compelling the district to cut 
77 million more from the 199091 budget 
school officials havent decided yet how to parcel out the cuts 
but a number of reform ideas have already been shelved or reduced 
a bilingual master plan designed to help nonenglish speaking 
students in all major subject areas has been only partially funded 
the district is also postponing expansion of its schoolbased 
management program in which more than 60 schools participate 
devastating would not be too strong a word said school 
board member rita walters it just socks it to us 
new york citys school board must come up with 268 million in 
instructional cuts this fall after having already eliminated some 
350 jobs at the central board 
how that will be done is the unanswered question said susan 
amlung a spokeswoman for the united federation of teachers 
the district is likely to cut school aides and 
paraprofessionals measures that the union fears will put more 
students in alreadyovercrowded classes school officials insist 
that wont happen kindergarten classes currently average 248 
pupils and highschool classes of 40 or more are not uncommon 
seattles 2436 million school budget has meant eliminating 165 
teaching administrative and other positions mainly through 
attrition 
its been a difficult time said seattle schools budget 
manager george steinhofer weve taken a number of reductions in 
central administration and this year we took reductions in special 
education and bilingual programs the only place left to look is in 
basic educational programs 
new orleans is closing two of its three centers for problem 
students and 60 school employees were laid off to balance the 358 
million budget said superintendent everett williams 
thats been the story of our life in this school district for 
the past four or five years i have had no budget thats been an 
even budget where i have been able to start off the year with no 
cuts at all he said 
in houston superintendent joan raymond is pushing for a record 
18 percent tax rate hike to fund a 7979 million budget the 
proposed budget would provide a 10 percent pay raise for teachers 
31 new principals and deans a dropout prevention program beefed 
up security a principal performance incentive program and funding 
of a massive construction program 
but some taxpayers are resisting 
by no extent of the imagination is the public going along with 
this said john pellicciotti a board member of the taxpayers 
coalition of greater houston 
not all cities are in such dire straits 
in atlanta public schools comptroller lawrence thompson said 
the district has not had cuts next years budget is 3313 
million compared with 3193 million this past school year 
weve been pretty fortunate thompson said 
newark with a 421 million school budget has an 85 million 
shortfall but has largely avoided layoffs some assistant 
principals and other administrators may be demoted to save money 
said spokesman kirk smith 
next year the district will get as much as 50 million in 
additional funds as part of a state plan to boost the quality of 
