<TEXT>
theres gold in them thar peaks and mark 
frost and david lynch are not above trying to mine it 
the richly textured twin peaks laden with 14 emmy 
nominations and unchecked praise from tv critics is going 
commercial as in books tapes records cherry pie and coffee 
yes executive producers frost and lynch who have tended to put 
art above profit want to make a bigger buck from their surreal 
nighttime soap opera 
the way they figure it someone is going to cash in on the cult 
following surrounding their saga of sex and murder and dancing 
midgets and a woman who carries around a log all the time and it 
might as well be them 
like their show however lynch and frosts approach is slightly 
off kilter this is not your average merchandising campaign of 
tshirts hats and buttons 
but then there is precious little that is ordinary about 
television advertising and marketing campaigns these days with 
changing federal network regulations and an increasingly fierce 
battle for viewers the landscape of tv promotions is being plowed 
under 
cbs and nbc are launching mammoth commercial campaigns in 
concert with such bastions of the american middle class as k mart 
and mcdonalds 
simon and schuster will publish the secret diary of laura 
palmer the high school homecoming queen whose murder propelled 
twin peaks 
the book written in 1 months by lynchs 22yearold daughter 
jennifer will hit the stands in time for the sept 30 premiere of 
the second season of her fathers show but thats not all 
the twin peaks tapes of agent cooper chronicling 
coffeeguzzling fbi agent dale coopers rambling cassette 
dissertations to his secretary will hit stores at about the same 
time 
also in the works a line of twin peaks coffee and cherry 
pie 
and while networks and individual programs are selling 
themselves with an unprecedented fervor it is for entirely 
different reasons 
the networks want to lure viewers program producers want to 
make money 
no one involved in primetime television merchandising for shows 
such as twin peaks or cartoon superstars the simpsons would 
say how much they make from program products 
but playmates toys inc sold 115 million last year in teenage 
mutant ninja turtle items ranging from pizza to underwear trade 
estimates put last years income from merchandise inspired by 
television and movies at 3 billion 
in the case of twin peaks we had some serious debate over 
whether we should get into the commercial aspect of 
merchandising said ken scherer chief operating officer and 
camp counselor of lynchfrost productions we figured look 
other people are doing it so we might as well do it 
the other people scherer was referring to are the unlicensed 
sellers of twin peaks tshirts cropping up in los angeles and 
new york that read i killed laura palmer and who shot agent 
cooper 
added scherer theres an awful lot of money out there for 
other people who are illegally selling twin peaks 
merchandise when independent production companies such as his 
launch merchandising campaigns scherer said profits are used to 
enhance the quality of programming 
the money that comes back you can put on the screen scherer 
said independent production companies dont have the money that 
big networks do 
such producers may not have networksized budgets but they do 
for the most part own the licensing rights to their shows abc 
cbs and nbc produce only a limited number of programs broadcast on 
their networks thus they have been barred from merchandising 
specific shows 
in november that will change with the lifting of federal 
communications commission regulations that ban networks from 
producing more than five hours of primetime programming each week 
when the fcc ceiling is obliterated abc cbs and nbc can produce 
as much of primetimes 22 programming hours as they want 
television executives said the fcc rules change is likely to 
result in networks playing a much larger role in merchandising 
campaigns 
until then however the primary focus of the networks 
marketing strategy is getting viewers to watch their programs not 
selling them books toys key chains or coffee mugs 
the power of advertising and television will reach thousands 
and thousands of more people than will ever see a twin peaks 
mug said george schweitzer senior vice president of 
communications for cbs broadcast group 
cbs is repeating its behemoth campaign with k marts 2300 
stores this fall last year in the biggest television contest of 
its kind the eye network gave away 6 million prizes from cars to 
vcrs to coffee mugs 
attention k mart shoppers this year cbs has upped the ante 
more cars will be given away along with 10 million twolitre 
bottles of pepsi and a grand prize of 250000 in mastercard funds 
according to schweitzer last years campaign increased fall 
premiere viewership by 28 percent players matched the numbers on 
game cards obtained at k mart stores with figures broadcast during 
certain cbs programs 
the new campaign which begins sept 26 is part of the 
networks strategy to lure moneyspending babyboomers cbs has 
even signed the temptations to sing their motown hit get ready 
but with eye network lyrics in commercials promoting the fall 
season 
product merchandising schweitzer said is lucrative for only a 
short time and only with giant hits such as foxs the simpsons 
these things are interesting as gimmicks schweitzer said 
but they pale in comparison to the power of a summers worth of 
television commercials 
and schweitzer added networks dont have to pay for their own 
air time each network spends about 40 to 50 million a year 
on advertising in addition to production costs for inhouse 
commercials promoting their shows schweitzer said if we had to 
pay for air time that would cost about 400 to 500 million 
next month nbc begins a 35 million contest with mcdonalds 
tied to its fall schedule said john miller executive vice 
president of marketing for the network weve never done anything 
quite this large before he said 
probably because competition between the four networks cable 
and video rentals has never been this intense nor has viewership 
in general ever dropped so much according to ratings vehemently 
disputed by cbs nbc and abc from the ac nielsen co 
still abc has hung back from the contest route taken by its 
competitors 
ultimately its our philosophy that people watch the show 
because theres something in the show that intrinsically interests 
them said mark zakarin vice president of marketing for abc 
entertainment our fall campaign really focuses on the stars of 
our shows no one watches a television show because of a singing 
group 
the bottom line for network marketing strategies is that 
contests and advertisements help get viewers to sample a new show 
but new car or no viewers wont come back unless they like the 
program 
people watch tv shows they dont watch fall campaigns 
zakarin said 
meanwhile independent and studioproduced shows continue to 
exploit merchandising as a way to make more money 
