kansas gov mike haydens nearloss in a 
threeway republican primary last week is the latest evidence that 
1990 is turning into a mean campaign season for incumbents 
voters have lots of reasons to be dissatisfied with government 
among them the savings and loan crisis the federal budget deficit 
and the weakened economy their discontent already is shaping some 
of the 36 governors races this year 
theres a loss of confidence in government said arkansas 
gov bill clinton who is having his own difficulties as he seeks a 
fifth term 
theres a reserve of cynicism in the electorate for a variety 
of reasons said mark gearan director of the democratic 
governors association theres a concern among incumbents but 
every state takes on a different hue and cast 
hayden won renomination in kansas by fewer than 8000 votes and 
3 percentage points after trailing through most of a long night of 
vote counting tuesday 
haydens political troubles stemmed from changes in the property 
tax system that had resulted in big tax increases for many kansans 
his predecessor former gov john carlin who shared some of the 
heat for tax changes dating back to his term lost a comeback bid 
and the democratic nomination by fewer than 1800 votes to joan 
finney veteran state treasurer 
an incumbents advantage is strong through the ability to raise 
money generate publicity and use the powers of government yet 
kansas is hardly alone in its unease with incumbents 
next door in nebraska republican gov kay orr is at the top of 
the gop endangered list as she seeks a second term 
shes in trouble over tax increases and her belated admission 
that taxes had indeed been raised to bolster her campaign shes 
hosted visits from president bush barbara bush and vice president 
dan quayle ronald reagan is expected to show up too 
another shaky republican florida gov bob martinez is 
considered vulnerable because of his opposition to abortion his 
vacillation on taxes and general doubts about his management 
ability hes presented the democrats with an opportunity to 
capture the governorship of one of the largest states and one that 
