<TEXT>
piracy the centuriesold scourge 
of the sea is making a comeback in brazil 
brazilian authorities have been unable to stop modern buccaneers 
who raid cargo ships and terrorize crews in ports along the 
southeastern coast 
piracy is getting worse and more violent said joao 
dilermando goncalves chief fleet inspector of lloyd brasileiro 
the countrys largest shipping company pirates have attacked three 
lloyd ships in rio this year 
the new pirates are different from the sneak thieves who always 
have plagued merchant ships goncalves said 
these are highly organized gangs of up to a dozen armed men 
he said they intimidate the crew and break containers open 
real heavy assault 
although todays pirates use speedboats uzi submachine guns and 
radio communications their methods have changed little from the 
days when buccaneers prowled the south american coast in sailing 
ships 
a typical attack occurs at night when most crew members are 
ashore 
one of the gang tosses a grappling hook and rope over the side 
or climbs up the anchor chain goncalves said he overpowers 
the duty officer and lowers the ships ladder just like in the old 
days 
while some of the raiders hold the crew at gunpoint others go 
for the cargo they take cables binoculars bearings 
chronometers electronic appliances even the ships compass 
goods containers are a favorite target 
they know beforehand whats inside said helcio muniz 
president of the national union of merchant marine officers they 
only go for the containers that have valuable cargo 
crews are virtually helpless muniz said ship rules do not 
allow crewmen to carry guns and the deck watchman the unions 
require also is unarmed 
piracy became a serious problem in brazil about two years ago 
said meton soares jr president of the national union of shipping 
companies 
brazilian ports are as dangerous as singapore hong kong and 
bangkok were decades ago before economic prosperity brought 
improved security he said in an interview 
about 40 percent of pirate attacks in brazil occur in santos 
latin americas largest port about 280 miles southwest of rio 
soares said 
last year 55 ships reported losses from piracy in santos but 
many others were attacked and did not bother to file complaints he 
said 
the federal police began acting with rigor there soares 
said but piracy continues and now it has spread to rio 
rio is ideal for such marauders ships awaiting dock space ride 
at anchor for days in the middle of the guanabara bay miles from 
land and are easy prey 
pirates gravitated to brazil centuries ago because of its 
4593mile coastline and many natural ports the word buccaneer 
is from a french term for early pirates who used the boucan a 
brazilian grill for roasting meat 
english and french pirates raided portuguese coastal settlements 
in brazil as early as the 16th century and later attacked ships 
carrying gold and gemstones to europe they were not driven off 
until the 19th century 
lloyd brasileiro has strengthened its duty watches and improved 
onboard lighting to combat the latest outbreak of piracy anchor 
hatches are covered and the ships ladder is raised at dusk 
goncalves said there even was a suggestion to put left and right 
shoes in separate containers of export footwear to discourage 
pirates but he admitted the precautions were not enough 
the problem is the bays are not policed he said we need 
armed uniformed naval vigilance 
robbery on the sea is the responsibility of federal police but 
they dont have boats and patrolling harbors is difficult 
police dont have the equipment to act on the water soares 
said by the time a pirate attack is reported thats often as 
far as it gets 
vice adm sergio doherty director of coasts and ports for the 
brazilian navy said neither the navy nor police was equipped to 
fight piracy 
what we need is a coast guard like the united states or 
argentina doherty said 
the government shelved a proposal to create a coast guard in the 
early 1980s 
soares said the police have enough problems fighting crime on 
land and he sees little chance of curbing piracy soon 
