<TEXT>
researchers have identified a new threat to the 
atmosphere with the discovery that the burning of tropical forests 
is releasing large amounts of nitrogen into the atmosphere 
tropical forest destruction has been known to contribute to the 
warming of the earths atmosphere by the release of carbon dioxide 
as carbon dioxide in the atmosphere increases the atmosphere traps 
more of the suns heat giving rise to the socalled greenhouse 
effect 
a study reported in the current issue of the journal nature 
finds that the burning of tropical forests also is releasing 
significant amounts of nitrogen some of it in the form of nitrous 
oxide a potent greenhouse gas 
nitrous oxide put into the atmosphere by biomass burning is a 
greenhouse gas 250 times more powerful molecule for molecule than 
carbon dioxide said joel s levine of nasas langley research 
center in hampton va in a commentary on the new study 
the burning of tropical forest biomass is also releasing 
nitric oxide which contributes to pollution and is the fastest 
growing component of acid rain levine said 
the study was directed by paul j crutzen of the max planck 
institute for chemistry in mainz west germany 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
study says 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
nursing home residents became less depressed 
when their caregivers were given rosy but bogus predictions 
about their progress a study says 
the residents also became more dependent on help for performing 
daytoday tasks researchers said 
both changes may have occurred because the caregivers spoke more 
warmly to them and physically helped them more researchers 
suggested in the july issue of the journal of the american 
geriatrics society 
the study focused on 63 elderly people newly admitted to six 
nursing homes they were randomly assigned to a highexpectancy 
group or a comparison group 
nurses and aides were told that members of the first group could 
be expected to do better than average compared with other residents 
with the same sorts of problems no such prediction was given for 
members of the comparison group 
on average members of the experimental group showed a decline 
in depressive symptoms within three months while those in the 
other group showed an increase but the highexpectancy residents 
became more dependent on physical help while the other group 
became less dependent 
previous research has linked increased helping by caregivers to 
a decrease in functional abilities the researchers said 
study authors were from harvard university beth israel hospital 
in boston and the brocktonwest roxbury veterans administration 
medical center in boston 
