<TEXT>
by now jim wells is used to the 
laughs evoked by his product cow boots 
but he says the number of dairy farmers who find it the perfect 
answer to serious hoof problems is increasing 
thats everybodys first reaction its comical to see a cow 
wearing a boot said wells 
they come over make a joke about it then ask what the boot 
is for then ive got them 
wells is attending new yorks empire farm days in seneca falls 
to find buyers and distributors in the united states for his 
shoes for moos since introducing the boot last august wells 
has sold more than 15000 at 50 apiece in eight countries 
including canada the soviet union and japan 
the response has been unbelievable said wells a parttime 
marketing instructor at conestoga college in elmira ontario and 
the owner of a clothing store 
paul larkin a dairy farmer from hamilton ny grinned as he 
looked over wells boot recently at the new york farm trade show 
he walked away with one under his arm 
its bad news when you have a cow with hoof rot or some other 
kind of foot infection im always looking for the better way and 
this looked like one larkin said 
the boot which looks like a shorter version of a firefighters 
boot is made of black fabricbacked rubber with two bright 
yellow straps and buckles to hold it in place it has a textured 
pebble bottom for traction on slippery surfaces 
its designed to protect the injured hoofs of cows while they 
heal normally when a cow develops hoof rot corns ulcers or 
other foot infections the cow is given antibiotics and the foot is 
bandaged and wrapped with plastic bags to keep the dressing dry 
plastic bags as you can imagine arent the best fit cows 
will rub them chew at them or whatever until they come off said 
wells they cant do that with the boot 
another benefit is that bootclad hooves dont need to be 
treated with antibiotics that saves the farmer milk which must be 
thrown away while a cow is on antibiotics and the cost of 
prescriptions which can cost as much as 170 wells said 
its a smart idea said everette bridgeman a dairy farm 
worker from bergen ny 
weve used old rubbers but they dont last long ive heard of 
other farmers using disposable diapers something thats durable 
and works is what farmers are looking for said bridgeman 
customers with problems like bridgemans gave wells the idea for 
his reusable cow boot 
three years ago i didnt know a thing about cows but a 
couple of mennonite farmers came into my store and bought rubber 
boots for their cows after talking to them i realized there was 
untapped niche there he said 
there are 2 million dairy cows in canada and 11 million in the 
united states capturing just 1 percent of those markets would mean 
sales of 65 million 
