<TEXT>
iraqs invasion of kuwait should build support 
in congress for requiring major improvements in automobile fuel 
efficiency environmentalists and consumer advocates say 
our troops in the middle east may have to pay the ultimate 
sacrifice bill magavern of the us public interest research 
group said wednesday encouraging conservation through greater 
fuel economy is relatively painless 
legislation is pending in congress to require 40 
milespergallon fuel efficiency by the end of the decade up from 
the current standard of 275 mpg 
automakers who fiercely oppose the bill acknowledge the middle 
east crisis could make their lobbying more difficult 
were afraid its going to be harder to fight said charles 
lockwood general counsel of the association of international 
automobile manufacturers we fear the senate may take action 
without considering all the consequences 
the bill sponsored by sen richard bryan dnev cleared the 
senate commerce committee on a 144 vote april 3 floor debate is 
expected next month 
we have been reminded that we squandered the breathing space 
of the 1980s not using that period of low prices constructively 
to lessen our dependence on foreign oil bryan said 
more than 50 senators support the bill and iraqs invasion of 
kuwait and its aftermath may provide the 60 votes needed to halt a 
filibuster magavern said 
under current law new car fleets all the cars a company 
manufactures in a model year are required to average at least 
275 miles per gallon the bryan bill would require each company to 
boost its average 20 percent by the 1995 model year and 40 percent 
by 2001 
the typical fleet would average 344 mpg in 1995 and 402 mpg by 
2001 
supporters say higher mileage standards are needed to force the 
auto industry to make more fuelefficient cars in addition to 
saving oil improved efficiency would reduce air pollution they 
say 
automakers say the bills targets are technologically 
unrealistic and would require drastic reductions in automobile 
weight all but the smallest cars would disappear from showrooms 
they warn and many consumers would hold onto their old gas 
guzzlers rather than crowd the family into a subcompact 
its an attempt to legislate the family car out of 
existence general motors corp spokesman bill noack said 
when the first gasoline shortages hit in the 1970s domestic 
auto companies had no fuelefficient cars to sell ford motor co 
vice president helen petrauskas said 
now however we have numerous small and midsize highly 
fuelefficient cars and trucks available she said we could 
adjust production volumes to accommodate greater consumer demand 
automakers will watch closely to see whether the latest oil 
scare rekindles interest in smaller cars chrysler corp spokesman 
richard muller said if so manufacturers will meet the demand 
but even then the bryan standards would not be feasible he said 
sales trends have been toward larger cars for the past eight 
years muller said this is the age of cheap gasoline he said 
its still priced very reasonably compared to other countries 
adjusted for inflation he said gasoline actually sells for less 
than during the early 1970s 
transportation secretary samuel skinner notified congress in 
march that the bush administration opposed the bill a spokesman 
said developments in the middle east had not altered that position 
