playboy can only sell two of four posters based 
on drawings keith haring had done for the magazine and it must 
tell buyers they were not authorized by the late pop artist 
according to an outofcourt settlement 
the settlement was announced wednesday 
harings estate filed suit in june in us district court in 
manhattan against playboy enterprises inc claiming copyright 
infringement and deceptive trade practices 
the posters were being sold along with certificates of 
authenticity for up to 600 said peter stern attorney for the 
keith haring foundation the posters are worth only about 5 he 
said 
the estate also claimed that three of the four drawings had been 
colorized at least one was altered and harings signature was 
added to two of them 
under the settlement chicagobased playboy agreed to recall and 
cease marketing two of the posters stern said 
the other two must bear a disclaimer stating this work was 
made without the participation of keith haring or his estate 
playboy also agreed not to issue certificates of 
authenticity or to use the haring trademark or logo 
the settlement did not involve any payment of money by either 
party playboy said in a news release 
the haring estate playboy said agreed to stop selling and turn 
over to special editions ltd its inventory of haringdesigned 
tshirts that was published in playboy magazine in 1986 
special editions is a subsidiary of playboy enterprises 
