<DOCNO> AP900809-0189 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
its just after dawn as david whitehead 
maneuvers his boxy milk truck up the first driveway of the day at 
the house he grabs two halfgallons as he jumps out drops them 
into the insulated box then is off to his next stop 
the thud of cartons has replaced the clatter of bottles but 
otherwise this could be a scene from the 1940s when nearly every 
gallon of milk americans drank at home was delivered to their 
doorsteps 
his reassuring presence may not be as pervasive as it was 50 
years ago but the milkman is definitely back in connecticut and 
other parts of the country 
and hes updated for the 90s with a product list that rivals 
any small grocery store 
with more women working the convenience of having the product 
delivered to the home is more appealing because they have better 
things to do with their discretionary time says michael marcus 
president of marcus dairy in danbury conn 
there are enough people out there who want the service he 
said its just a matter of getting the word out 
nostalgia is part of the appeal marcus said his customers are 
clamoring to have their milk delivered in glass bottles partly for 
ecological reasons theyre recyclable but also for the memories 
they conjure up 
his milk now comes in plasticcoated paper cartons but he plans 
to bring back bottles as soon as he can find a manufacturer 
for the same reason drivers for the palm beach milk co in palm 
beach fla wear the traditional white uniform black bow tie and 
white hat marcus drivers wear gray uniforms sans hat 
the old axiom of the milkman being part of the family were 
fostering that image said jacques von spiro who started palm 
beach milk three months ago to cater to a growing market 
in connecticut 25 marcus trucks fan out across the state six 
days a week the 110 stops on whiteheads route include fancy 
beachfront estates modest homes in middleclass neighborhoods and 
small homes in public housing projects 
orders run the gamut one family gets a halfpint of cream 
delivered twice a week another gets practically everything marcus 
dairy offers eight varieties of milk orange and grapefruit juice 
cottage cheese sour cream eggs ice cream yogurt butter bacon 
and plastic trash bags 
fatfree beef will soon be offered on some routes and the dairy 
is negotiating with an independent grocer to deliver all groceries 
marcus said 
if i could have all my groceries delivered i would said 
patricia carrubba a customer on whiteheads route who has been 
getting her milk and orange juice delivered for two years 
marcus charges 192 for a halfgallon of homedelivered milk 
compared to a dollar and change in some stores thats enough of a 
difference to make the milkman the first to go when a family 
suffers a financial crunch said whitehead a beefy bearded 
42yearold who has been with marcus dairy for 21 years business 
also slows down during the summer he said 
michael marcus whose grandfather started the dairy in 1924 
says home milk delivery started to decline during the 1950s and 
1960s with the rise of the twocar family 
his deliveries dropped to their lowest point around 1978 but 
started to rebound slowly about five years ago today they account 
for about 9 percent of his business or about 7500 accounts 
marcus whose other customers include schools hospital and 
other institutions projects growth of 1 percent a month and hopes 
home deliveries will account for half his business within a couple 
of years 
von spiro said he researched the home delivery business for two 
years before starting palm beach milk in may with 208 customers 
he now has more than 1000 customers and hopes to expand in 
florida and across the country 
his company offers 98 products including baked goods and smoked 
salmon delivered in prepackaged coolerlike boxes the milk 
which comes in glass bottles is 199 a halfgallon 
just 1 percent of the 3 billion gallons of milk produced 
nationwide is delivered to the home according to the us 
department of agriculture but dairymen like marcus and von spiro 
see a growing if modest niche for the homedelivery business 
with both husbands and wives working theres not a lot of 
time von spiro said they appreciate this 
von spiro said his typical palm beach customers arent 
spectacularly wealthy but working couples between the ages of 25 
and 50 most without children 
in addition to yuppies marcuss connecticut drivers also serve 
some lowerincome families and elderly shutins who cant get to 
the market 
for some customers like vera cole with a mansion on long island 
sound delivery simply makes life easier 
i find i spend less money on groceries because if i get milk 
and orange juice from the milkman i dont make as many trips to 
the grocery store she said 
</TEXT>
