the securities and exchange commission filed a 
complaint thursday alleging fraud and stock manipulation during the 
public offering and subsequent trading of overthecounter 
securities of a new jersey manufacturing company 
the firm beres industries inc of lakewood nj two of its 
officers and the president and three traders of the nowdefunct 
brokerage that executed the offering were named in the lawsuit 
filed in newark njs federal court 
the complaint seeks more than 1 million in alleged illegal 
profits from beres chairman charles beres and his son and company 
president charles beres jr 
it also seeks unspecified profits from the brokerage employees 
sec attorney david miller said the firm monmouth investments inc 
made about 3 million through the alleged illegal practices 
the sec said beres sr and monmouth president arden r brown 
failed to disclose to regulators an agreement in which beres would 
sell 12 million shares of his privately held securities to 
monmouth at belowmarket prices 
the complaint further alleged that after the july 1986 public 
offering monmouth dominated the market of beres securities through 
boiler room selling tactics and artificially manipulated the 
stock price through various schemes 
monmouth a former member of the national association of 
securities dealers was based in englishtown nj and had 14 
branch offices with about 10000 customer accounts it went out of 
business in march 1989 
