<TEXT>
scheringplough corp announced thursday 
that it was withdrawing from the market a blood pressurereducing 
drug that has been linked to isolated cases of liver damage 
though the number of toxicity cases was quite small in 
relation to the number of patients using dilevalol our decision 
was taken in the best interest of the potential patient population 
for the drug alexander z lane president of scheringplough 
research said in a statement 
the company said it was halting the sale of dilevalol in japan 
and portugal the only two countries where it is sold over the 
counter a pending marketing application before the federal food 
and drug administration will be withdrawn the company said 
company spokesman linn weiss said liver toxicity developed in 17 
of 176000 patients who had been taking the drug as part of 
worldwide clinical trials or under the care of a physician 
in all but one of the 17 cases flulike symptoms and fatigue 
disappeared after the medication was discontinued weiss said a 
japanese man taking the drug died but weiss said medical experts 
could not link his death definitively to the antihypertensive drug 
sales of dilevalol in the first eight months since it was 
introduced overseas totalled about 20 million the company said 
withdrawing the drug from the market will not affect 
scheringploughs financial performance or its projected earnings 
per share this year the company said 
