<TEXT>
united airlines workers and stock market 
investors indicated thursday they were encouraged by a decision 
extending the life of an employee buyout bid 
but the twomonth reprieve granted late wednesday by ual corp 
uniteds parent company offered no guarantee that the 438 
billion 201pershare deal will get done 
indeed there is some concern that a provision allowing uals 
board to call off the deal at any time could hamper the buyout 
groups ability to obtain financing commitments by the new oct 9 
deadline 
steven matthews a spokesman for the unionled buyout group 
declined comment thursday on that possibility he said the group 
was going forward and hoped to arrange financing commitments as 
quickly as possible 
matthews also declined comment on a wall street journal report 
that the buyout group had requested a threemonth extension 
ual stock initially rose on the new york stock exchange trading 
as high as 123 but it closed at 11375 down 75 cents 
without the deadline extension the bid to make united the 
worlds largest employeeowned company would have expired thursday 
the buyout group blamed its failure to line up loan commitments 
on the middle east crisis which it said had slowed the progress 
of its discussions with financing sources according to a 
statement issued wednesday by ual 
the iraqi invasion of kuwait last week has caused airline fuel 
prices to soar and airline stock prices to drop presumably making 
united a greater credit risk 
airline analyst robert decker of duff amp phelps inc in chicago 
said the middle east situation provides a convenient alibi 
it certainly is a factor he said but the way events were 
unfolding it didnt seem the group would have financing arranged 
by the deadline anyway 
decker said the extension gives the buyout group more time to 
either find financing or restructure its proposal perhaps to 
reduce the 155pershare cash component of the offer 
ual indicated though that it would not accept a lower total 
bid 
skepticism about the buyout mounted in recent weeks after three 
large new york banks chase manhattan corp chemical banking 
corp and citicorp withdrew from a group of banks that had begun 
loan talks with the buyout group 
the banks indicated they might be willing to make the loans if 
the buyout group obtains other financing from nonbank sources the 
group reportedly is negotiating with a number of aircraft 
manufacturers and parts suppliers for such financing 
at least three other banks bankers trust new york corp 
manufacturers hanover corp and security pacific corp are 
continuing to discuss loan possibilities with the buyout group 
